answer: Mother Teresa, born Agnes Gonxha Bojaxhiu, was a Roman Catholic nun and missionary. She was born in Skopje, Macedonia, then part of the Ottoman Empire. answer: Elvis Presley (January 8, 1935 – August 16, 1977) was an American singer and actor. Regarded as one of the most significant cultural icons of the 20th century, he is often referred to as "the King of Rock and Roll", or simply, "the King". His music career began there in 1954, when he began to work with Sam Phillips, the owner of Sun Records. Accompanied by guitarist Scotty Moore and bassist Bill Black, Presley was an early popularizer of rockabilly, an uptempo, backbeat-driven fusion of country music and rhythm and blues. RCA Victor acquired his contract in a deal arranged by Colonel Tom Parker, who would manage the singer for more than two decades. Presley's first RCA single, "Heartbreak Hotel", released in January 1956, was a number-one hit. He became the leading figure of the newly popular sound of rock and roll with a series of network television appearances and chart-topping records. His energized interpretations of songs and sexually provocative performance style, combined with a singularly potent mix of influences across color lines that coincided with the dawn of the Civil Rights Movement, made him enormously popular—and controversial.

answer: Caspian Sea is the largest enclosed body of water on Earth by area, variously classed as the world's largest lake or a full-fledged sea. It is an endorheic basin (it has no outflows) located between Europe and Asia. It is bounded to the north by Russia, to the south by Iran, to the west by Azerbaijan and to the east by Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, and Russia. The Caspian Sea is divided into three distinct parts: the North Caspian, the Middle Caspian, and the South Caspian. The North Caspian is the smallest of the three parts, with a salinity of 12 psu, about a third of that of ocean water. The Middle Caspian has a salinity of 10 psu, and the South Caspian has a salinity of 7 psu. The Caspian Sea is classified as an inland sea because of its landlocked nature, although it is occasionally called a lake. It has an area of 371,000 km2 (143,000 sq mi) and a volume of 78,200 km3 (18,800 cu mi).

The series follows the misadventures of alcoholic scientist Rick Sanchez and his easily influenced grandson Morty Smith, who split their time between domestic family life and interdimensional adventures. Roiland voices the series' eponymous characters. The series has its origins in an animated parody of Back to the Future created by Roiland for film festival Channel 101. Adult Swim approached Roiland to create the series after seeing the shorts.

The Spartans were forced to surrender, and their city was sacked and burned to the ground.

topic: Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago), Chicago
answer: Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago) is a science museum located in Chicago, Illinois. It is housed in the former Palace of Fine Arts from the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition. The museum is home to the largest indoor captive display of locomotives in the United States. The museum is also home to a full-size replica coal mine, a World War II German submarine, a 72-foot (22 m) tall steam locomotive, a 40-foot (12 m) tall tornado simulator, a 3,500 square feet (330 m2) model railroad, and a 5-story-tall mirrored kaleidoscope.
